# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oxford-university-press
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The building was built as a county hall for Berkshire, Abingdon being Berkshire's county town; it was to serve as the principal sessions house and administrative home for the Justices of the county.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The county hall was designed in the Baroque style by Christopher Kempster who trained with Sir Christopher Wren on St Paul's Cathedral.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] It stands on large pilasters with a sheltered area beneath for use as a market or other municipal functions and was completed in 1683.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] Nikolaus Pevsner said of the building: "Of the free-standing town halls of England with open ground floors this is the grandest".
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] It housed a courtroom for the assizes until 1867 when Abingdon ceded that role to Reading Assize Courts.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] Following the completion of a major restoration of the building, Queen Elizabeth II, visited the town hall, signed the visitor's book and unveiled a plaque in November 1956.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The museum's collections were started in 1919.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The museum has permanent collections and presents temporary exhibitions several times a year.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] There are also smaller exhibitions on local themes that are changed every month.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The Monks' Map of the River Thames around Abingdon in the 16th century has been held at the town's Guildhall since 1907.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] A reproduction of the Anglo-Saxon Abingdon Sword, discovered in the river at Abingdon and held by the Ashmolean Museum in Oxford, has also been put on display.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] In December 2011, with the help of British Motor Heritage, the last MGB Roadster sports car, which came off the production line in Abingdon in 1980 was lifted through a window 30 feet up, for display in the museum's main gallery.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] From 2010 to 2012, the museum and building underwent a two-year restoration programme, partly funded by the National Lottery.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] The museum was informally reopened to visitors by Martha Howe-Douglas, an actress in the BBC television series *Horrible Histories*, in July 2012 and was officially reopened by the Duke of Gloucester on 8 March 2013.
[src:oxford-university-press/abingdon-county-hall-museum] A new museum café was established in the basement.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] An **academic journal** or **scholarly journal** is a periodical publication in which scholarship relating to a particular academic discipline is published.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] They serve as permanent and transparent forums for the dissemination, scrutiny, and discussion of research.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Unlike professional magazines or trade magazines, the articles are mostly written by researchers rather than staff writers employed by the journal.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] They nearly universally require peer review for research articles or other scrutiny from contemporaries competent and established in their respective fields.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Academic journals trace their origins back to the 17th century, with the *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society* being established in 1665 as the first scientific journal.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] As of 2012, it is estimated that over 28,100 active academic journals are in publication, with scopes ranging from the general sciences, as seen in journals like *Science* and *Nature*, to highly specialized fields.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] These journals publish a variety of articles including original research, review articles, and perspectives.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The advent of electronic publishing has made academic journals more accessible.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Content usually takes the form of articles presenting original research, review articles, or book reviews.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The term *academic journal* applies to scholarly publications in all fields; this includes journals that cover formal sciences, natural sciences, social sciences, and humanities, which differ somewhat from each other in form and function.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Academic journals in the formal and natural sciences are often called *scientific journals*.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Most journals are highly specialized, although some of the oldest journals such as *Science* and *Nature* publish articles and scientific papers across a wide range of scientific fields.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Although academic journals are superficially similar to professional magazines (or trade journals), they are quite different.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Articles in academic journals are written by active researchers such as students, scientists, and professors.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Their intended audience is others in the field, meaning their content is highly technical.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Academic articles also deal with research and are peer-reviewed.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Meanwhile, trade journals are aimed at people in different fields, focusing on how people in those fields can do their jobs better.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Active academic researchers are expected to publish their work in academic journals, and public funding bodies often require research results to be published in academic journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Academic credentials for promotion into academic ranks are established in large part by the number and impact of scientific articles published.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] This places pressure on researchers to publish articles frequently – an environment known as *publish or perish*.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the 17th century, scientists wrote letters to each other and included scientific ideas with them.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Then, in the mid-17th century, scientists began to hold meetings and share their scientific ideas.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Eventually, they led to the start of organizations, such as the Royal Society (1660) and the French Academy of Sciences (1666).
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The idea of a published journal with the purpose of "[letting] people know what is happening in the Republic of Letters" was first conceived by François Eudes de Mézeray in 1663.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] A publication titled *Journal littéraire général* was supposed to be published to fulfill that goal, but never was.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Humanist scholar Denis de Sallo (under the pseudonym "Sieur de Hédouville") and printer Jean Cusson took Mazerai's idea, and obtained a royal privilege from King Louis XIV on 8 August 1664 to establish the *Journal des sçavans*.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The journal's first issue was published on 5 January 1665.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] 4. report on the proceedings and censures of both secular and ecclesiastical courts, as well as those of universities both in France and outside.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Soon after, the Royal Society established *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society* in March 1665, and the *Académie des Sciences* established the **Mémoires de l'Académie des Sciences** in 1666, which focused on scientific communications.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] By the end of the 18th century, nearly 500 such periodicals had been published, the vast majority coming from Germany (304 periodicals), France (53), and England (34).
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Several of those publications, in particular the German journals, tended to be short-lived (under five years).
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Meadows has estimated the proliferation of journals to reach 10,000 journals in 1950, and 71,000 in 1987.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Michael Mabe wrote that the estimates will vary depending on the definition of what exactly counts as a scholarly publication, but that the growth rate has been "remarkably consistent over time", with an average rate of 3.46% per year from 1800 to 2003.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In 1733, *Medical Essays and Observations* was established by the Medical Society of Edinburgh as the first fully peer-reviewed journal.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Peer review was introduced as an attempt to increase the quality and pertinence of submissions.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Peer review did not begin until the 1970s, and was seen as a way of enabling researchers who were not as well-known to have their papers published in journals that were more prestigious.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Though it was originally done by mailing copies of papers to reviewers, it is now done online.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Upon receipt of a submitted article, editors at the journal determine whether to reject the submission outright or begin the process of peer review.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the latter case, the submission becomes subject to review by outside scholars of the editor's choosing who typically remain anonymous.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Though these reports are generally confidential, some journals and publishers also practice public peer review.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The editors either choose to reject the article, ask for a revision and resubmission, or accept the article for publication.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Even accepted articles are often subjected to further (sometimes considerable) editing by journal editorial staff before they appear in print.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The peer review can take from several weeks to several months.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Many journal articles are broadly structured according to the IMRAD scheme.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Reading an article in an academic journal usually entails first reading the title, to see if it is related to the desired topic.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] If it is, the next step is to read the abstract (or summary or conclusion, if the abstract is missing), to determine if the article is worth reading.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Publishing research results is an essential part of helping science to advance.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] If scientists are describing experiments or calculations, they should also explain how they did them so that an independent researcher could repeat the experiment or calculation to verify the results, or so that they could evaluate whatever the research article's findings were.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Each journal article becomes part of the permanent scientific record.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Articles can also be categorized by their purpose.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Review articles, also called "reviews of progress", are checks on the research published in journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Some journals are devoted entirely to review articles, some contain a few in each issue, and others do not publish review articles.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Such reviews often cover the research from the preceding year, some for longer or shorter terms; some are devoted to specific topics, some to general surveys.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Some reviews are enumerative, listing all significant articles in a given subject; others are selective, including only what they think worthwhile.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Yet others are evaluative, judging the state of progress in the subject field.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Some journals are published in series, each covering a complete subject field year, or covering specific fields through several years.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Unlike original research articles, review articles tend to be solicited or "peer-invited" submissions, often planned years in advance, which may themselves go through a peer-review process once received.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] They are typically relied upon by students beginning a study in a given field, or for current awareness of those already in the field.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Reviews of scholarly books are checks upon the research books published by scholars; unlike articles, book reviews tend to be solicited.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Journals typically have a separate book review editor determining which new books to review and by whom.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] If an outside scholar accepts the book review editor's request for a book review, he or she generally receives a free copy of the book from the journal in exchange for a timely review.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Publishers send books to book review editors in the hope that their books will be reviewed.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The length and depth of research book reviews varies much from journal to journal, as does the extent of textbook and trade book review.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] An academic journal's prestige is established over time, and can reflect many factors, some but not all of which are expressible quantitatively.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In many fields, a formal or informal hierarchy of academic journals exists; the most prestigious journal in a field tends to be the most selective in terms of the articles it will select for publication, and usually will also have the highest impact factor.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In some countries, journal rankings can be utilized for funding decisions and even evaluation of individual researchers, although they are poorly suited for that purpose.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In each academic discipline, some journals receive a high number of submissions and opt to restrict how many they publish, keeping the acceptance rate low.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Size or prestige are not a guarantee of reliability.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the natural sciences and in the social sciences, the impact factor is an established proxy, measuring the number of later articles citing articles already published in the journal.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] There are other quantitative measures of prestige, such as the overall number of citations, how quickly articles are cited, and the average "half-life" of articles.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Clarivate Analytics' *Journal Citation Reports*, which among other features, computes an impact factor for academic journals, draws data for computation from the Science Citation Index Expanded (for natural science journals), and from the Social Sciences Citation Index (for social science journals).
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Several other metrics are also used, including the SCImago Journal Rank, CiteScore, Eigenfactor, and Altmetrics.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the Anglo-American humanities, there is no tradition (as there is in the sciences) of giving impact factors that could be used in establishing a journal's prestige.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Recent moves have been made by the European Science Foundation (ESF) to change the situation, resulting in the publication of preliminary lists for the ranking of academic journals in the humanities.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] These rankings have been severely criticized, notably by history and sociology of science British journals that have published a common editorial entitled "Journals under Threat".
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Though it did not prevent ESF and some national organizations from proposing journal rankings, it largely prevented their use as evaluation tools.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In some disciplines such as knowledge management/intellectual capital, the lack of a well-established journal ranking system is perceived by academics as "a major obstacle on the way to tenure, promotion and achievement recognition".
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Conversely, a significant number of scientists and organizations consider the pursuit of impact factor calculations as inimical to the goals of science, and have signed the San Francisco Declaration on Research Assessment to limit its use.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In business and management disciplines, the UK-based Chartered Association of Business Schools (CABS) and the Australian Business Deans Council (ABDC) publish journal rankings.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Many academic journals are subsidized by universities or professional organizations, and do not exist to make a profit.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] They often accept advertising, page and image charges from authors to pay for production costs.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] On the other hand, some journals are produced by commercial publishers who do make a profit by charging subscriptions to individuals and libraries.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] They may also sell all of their journals in discipline-specific collections or a variety of other packages.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Many scientists and librarians have long protested these costs, especially as they see these payments going to large for-profit publishing houses.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] To allow their researchers online access to journals, many universities purchase *site licenses*, permitting access from anywhere in the university, and, with appropriate authorization, by university-affiliated users at home or elsewhere.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] These may be much more expensive than the cost for a print subscription.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Despite the transition to electronic publishing, the costs of site licenses continue to rise relative to universities' budgets.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Journal editors tend to have other professional responsibilities, most often as teaching professors.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the case of the largest journals, there are paid staff assisting in the editing.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The production of the journals is almost always done by publisher-paid staff.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Humanities and social science academic journals are usually subsidized by universities or professional organization.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Traditional scientific journals require a paid subscription to access published articles.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The cost and value proposition of subscription to academic journals is being continuously reassessed by institutions worldwide.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Concerns about cost and open access have led to the creation of free-access journals such as the Public Library of Science (PLoS) family and partly open or reduced-cost journals such as the *Journal of High Energy Physics*.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] However, professional editors still have to be paid, and PLoS still relies heavily on donations from foundations to cover the majority of its operating costs; smaller journals do not often have access to such resources.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Open access journals may charge authors a fee for review or publication, rather than charging readers an access fee.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] While the ability to reproduce the results based only on details included in the article is expected, verification of reproducibility by a third party is not generally required for publication.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The reproducibility of results presented in an article is therefore judged implicitly by the quality of the procedures reported and agreement with the data provided.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] However, some journals in the field of chemistry such as *Inorganic Syntheses* and *Organic Syntheses* require independent reproduction of the results presented as part of the review process.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The inability for independent researchers to reproduce published results is widespread, with 70% of researchers reporting failure to reproduce another scientist's results, including more than half who report failing to reproduce their own experiments.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Sources of irreproducibility vary, including publication of falsified or misrepresented data and poor detailing of procedures.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Traditionally, the author of an article was required to transfer the copyright to the journal publisher.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Publishers claimed this was necessary in order to protect authors' rights, and to coordinate permissions for reprints or other use.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] However, many authors, especially those active in the open access movement, found this unsatisfactory, and have used their influence to effect a gradual move towards a license to publish instead.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Under such a system, the publisher has permission to edit, print, and distribute the article commercially, but the authors retain the other rights themselves.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Even if they retain the copyright to an article, most journals allow certain rights to their authors.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] These rights usually include the ability to reuse parts of the paper in the author's future work, and allow the author to distribute a limited number of copies.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] In the print format, such copies are called reprints; in the electronic format, they are called postprints.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The rise of open access journals, in which the author retains the copyright but must pay a publication charge, such as the Public Library of Science family of journals, is another recent response to copyright concerns.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The Internet has revolutionized the production of, and access to, academic journals, with their contents available online via services subscribed to by academic libraries.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Individual articles are subject-indexed in databases such as Google Scholar.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Given the goal of sharing scientific research to speed advances, open access has affected science journals more than humanities journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Commercial publishers are experimenting with open access models, but are trying to protect their subscription revenues.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Academic journals have been criticized for persistent gender, geographic, and other representation imbalances on editorial boards.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The much lower entry cost of online publishing has also raised concerns of an increase in publication of "junk" journals with lower publishing standards.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] These journals, often with names chosen as similar to well-established publications, solicit articles via e-mail and then charge the author to publish an article, often with no sign of actual review.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Jeffrey Beall, a research librarian at the University of Colorado, has compiled a list of what he considers to be "potential, possible, or probable predatory scholarly open-access publishers"; the list numbered over 300 journals as of April 2013, but he estimates that there may be thousands.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The OMICS Publishing Group, which publishes a number of the journals on this list, threatened to sue Beall in 2013 and Beall stopped publishing in 2017, citing pressure from his university.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] A US judge fined OMICS $50 million in 2019 stemming from an FTC lawsuit.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Some academic journals use the registered report format, which aims to counteract issues such as data dredging and hypothesizing after the results are known.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] For example, *Nature Human Behaviour* has adopted the registered report format, as it "shift[s] the emphasis from the results of research to the questions that guide the research and the methods used to answer them".
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The *European Journal of Personality* defines this format: "In a registered report, authors create a study proposal that includes theoretical and empirical background, research questions/hypotheses, and pilot data (if available).
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Some journals are *born digital* in that they are solely published on the web and in a digital format.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Though most electronic journals originated as print journals, which subsequently evolved to have an electronic version, while still maintaining a print component, others eventually became electronic-only.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] An **e-journal** closely resembles a print journal in structure: there is a table of contents which lists the articles, and many electronic journals still use a volume/issue model, although some titles now publish continuously.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Online journal articles are a specialized form of electronic document: they have the purpose of providing material for academic research and study, and they are formatted approximately like journal articles in traditional printed journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Often, a journal article will be available for download in two formats: PDF and HTML, although other electronic file types are often supported for supplementary material.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] New tools such as JATS and Utopia Documents provide a 'bridge' to the 'web-versions' in that they connect the content in PDF versions directly to the World Wide Web via hyperlinks that are created 'on-the-fly'.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] The PDF version of an article is usually seen as the version of record, but the matter is subject to some debate.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Articles are indexed in bibliographic databases as well as by search engines.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] E-journals allow new types of content to be included in journals, for example, video material, or the data sets on which research has been based.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] With the growth and development of the Internet, there has been a growth in the number of new digital-only journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] A subset of these journals exist as Open Access titles, meaning that they are free to access for all, and have Creative Commons licences which permit the reproduction of content in different ways.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] High quality open access journals are listed in Directory of Open Access Journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Most, however, continue to exist as subscription journals, for which libraries, organisations and individuals purchase access.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Benefits of electronically publishing include easy availability of supplementary materials (data, graphics and video), lower cost, and availability to more people, especially scientists from non-developed countries.
[src:oxford-university-press/academic-journals] Hence, research results from more developed nations are becoming more accessible to scientists from non-developed countries.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Alan Howarth was the son of Major Thomas Howarth MC (Chief Master of King Edward's School, Birmingham, Second Master of Winchester College and High Master of St.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Paul's School) and Margaret Teakle (who was a Wren in the Second World War).
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He was educated at Rugby School and gained a BA in History from King's College, Cambridge in 1965.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Howarth subsequently worked in the Conservative Party Chairman's office in Conservative Central Office under Willie Whitelaw and Peter Thorneycroft, before becoming director of the Conservative Research Department and party vice-chairman.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Having been appointed a Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the 1982 New Year Honours for political service, Howarth was Conservative Party MP for Stratford-on-Avon, first elected in 1983.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He was a founder member of the Thatcherite No Turning Back group.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He served as a whip, and was subsequently Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Education and Science from 1989 to 1992, becoming the architect of the polytechnics' transition to university status.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] On 7 October 1995, Howarth announced his resignation from the Conservative Party and defected to the Labour Party, the first MP to defect directly from the Conservatives to Labour, and the first former Conservative MP to sit as a Labour MP since Sir Oswald Mosley.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] The timing of the defection was crucial, as it immediately preceded the Conservative Party conference, the first since Prime Minister John Major had been challenged for the party leadership earlier in the year.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He wanted a new seat to contest as a Labour candidate and, after failing to win the seats of Wentworth and Wythenshawe and Sale East, he was selected for the safe Labour seat of Newport East in Wales.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] The National Union of Mineworkers leader Arthur Scargill stood against him under the Socialist Labour Party banner, but he easily held the seat for Labour.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] After the election victory of 1997, he was appointed Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Education and Employment, becoming Minister for the Arts at the Department of Culture, Media and Sport the following year.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He was also a member of the Privy Council.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He was dropped from the government after the 2001 general election, and stood down from the House of Commons at the 2005 general election.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Jessica Morden was selected to replace him as candidate by the Constituency Labour Party.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] By the time he stood down, he had spent only 18 months of his 22-year career as an MP on the opposition benches (October 1995 to May 1997).
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] On 15 June 2005, he was created a life peer as **Baron Howarth of Newport**, of Newport in the County of Gwent.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] In a House of Lords debate on the outcome of the European Union Referendum on 5 July 2016, Lord Howarth announced his support for Britain's departure from the European Union.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] They had two daughters (born 1974 and 1975) and two sons (born 1977 and April 1985).
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] He was later the partner of Labour peer Patricia Hollis who died in 2018.
[src:oxford-university-press/alan-howarth-baron-howarth-of-newport] Howarth died from cancer on 10 September 2025, at the age of 81.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was working with Israeli diplomats and preparing a major address supporting Israel to be timed for the state's seventh anniversary in 1955, but died shortly before he could give it.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein left his papers and literary estate to Hebrew University in Jerusalem, which he had help establish.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:oxford-university-press/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] Alexander was the partner who developed the literary reputation of the company, while Daniel took charge of the business and commercial side.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] Originally called *Macmillan & Co.*, the firm started as a successful bookshop in Cambridge.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] The brothers soon started publishing books as well as selling them.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] After Daniel's death in 1857, Alexander continued to run the firm.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] He expanded the company into a worldwide organization and also started publishing magazines, including the prestigious scientific journal *Nature*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] Macmillan assigned George Edward Brett to create the New York office in August 1869, and hired American firm Messrs.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] Pott & Amery to assist in the marketing and distribution of Macmillan's books.
[src:oxford-university-press/alexander-macmillan-publisher] Alexander's brother Daniel was the grandfather of Harold Macmillan, who became Prime Minister of the United Kingdom.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The novel received positive reviews upon release.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It is now one of the best-known works of Victorian literature; its narrative, structure, characters, and imagery have had a wide influence on popular culture and literature, especially in the fantasy genre.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It is credited as helping end an era of didacticism in children's literature, inaugurating an era in which writing for children aimed to "delight or entertain".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The tale plays with logic, giving the story lasting popularity with adults as well as with children.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The titular character, Alice, shares her name with Alice Liddell, a girl Carroll knew; scholars disagree about the extent to which the character was based upon her.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The novel has never been out of print and has been translated into 174 languages.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Its legacy includes adaptations to screen, radio, visual art, ballet, opera, and musical theatre as well as theme parks, board games, and video games.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll published a sequel in 1871 entitled *Through the Looking-Glass* and a shortened version for young children, *The Nursery "Alice"*, in 1890.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The journey began at Folly Bridge, Oxford, and ended 5 miles (8 km) upstream at Godstow, Oxfordshire.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] During the trip, Carroll told the girls a story that he described in his diary as "Alice's Adventures Under Ground", which his journal says he "undertook to write out for Alice".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice Liddell recalled that she asked Carroll to write it down: unlike other stories he had told her, this one she wanted to preserve.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She finally received the manuscript more than two years later.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The day 4 July was known as the "golden afternoon", prefaced in the novel as a poem.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In fact, the weather around Oxford on 4 July was "cool and rather wet", although at least one scholar has disputed this claim.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Scholars debate whether Carroll in fact came up with *Alice* during the "golden afternoon" or whether the story was developed over a longer period.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll had known the Liddell children since around March 1856, when he befriended Harry Liddell.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He had met Lorina by early March as well.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In June 1856, he took the children out on the river.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Robert Douglas-Fairhurst, who wrote a literary biography of Carroll, suggests that Carroll favoured Alice Pleasance Liddell in particular because her name was ripe for allusion.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] "Pleasance" means pleasure and the name "Alice" appeared in contemporary works, including the poem "Alice Gray" by William Mee, of which Carroll wrote a parody; Alice is a character in "Dream-Children: A Reverie", a prose piece by Charles Lamb.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll, an amateur photographer by the late 1850s, produced many photographic portraits of the Liddell children – and especially of Alice, of which 20 survive.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll began writing the manuscript of the story the next day, although that earliest version is lost.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The girls and Carroll took another boat trip a month later, when he elaborated the plot of the story to Alice, and in November, he began working on the manuscript in earnest.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] To add the finishing touches, he researched natural history in connection with the animals presented in the book and then had the book examined by other children—particularly those of George MacDonald.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Though Carroll did add his own illustrations to the original copy, on publication he was advised to find a professional illustrator so that the pictures were more appealing to his audience.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He subsequently approached *Punch* cartoonist John Tenniel to reinterpret his visions through his own artistic eye, telling him that the story had been well-liked by the children.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll began planning a print edition of the *Alice* story in 1863.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He wrote on 9 May 1863 that MacDonald's family had suggested he publish *Alice*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A diary entry for 2 July says that he received a specimen page of the print edition around that date.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] On 26 November 1864, Carroll gave Alice the manuscript of *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*, with illustrations by Carroll, dedicating it as "A Christmas Gift to a Dear Child in Memory of a Summer's Day".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The published version of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* is about twice the length of *Alice's Adventures Under Ground* and includes episodes, such as the Mad Hatter's Tea-Party, that do not appear in the manuscript.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The only known manuscript copy of *Under Ground* is held in the British Library.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Macmillan published a facsimile in 1886.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Sitting with her older sister on a bank, and feeling rather sleepy and bored, Alice suddenly spots a White Rabbit with a pocket watch and waistcoat hurrying by, lamenting that he is late.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Surprised, Alice follows him down a rabbit hole, which sends her into a lengthy fall.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Landing safely, she finds herself inside a room where she discovers a key to a tiny door, beyond which is a garden.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] While pondering how to fit through the door, she notices a bottle labelled "Drink me".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice drinks some of the contents and, to her astonishment, shrinks small enough to enter the door.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] However, she had left the key on a table and is now unable to reach it.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She finds and eats a cake labelled "Eat me", which causes her to grow to a tremendous size.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] As she cries, the White Rabbit rushes past, dropping a fan and gloves.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice uses the fan to cool herself down, which causes her to shrink once more and leaves her swimming in a pool of her own tears.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] There she meets various animals and birds, who convene on a bank and engage in a "Caucus Race" to dry themselves.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice inadvertently frightens the animals away by mentioning her cat.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Mistaking her for his maidservant, the White Rabbit orders Alice to go to his house and retrieve his lost gloves and fan.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice finds another bottle and drinks from it, causing her to grow to such an extent that she gets stuck in the house.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Attempting to extract her, the White Rabbit and his neighbours eventually take to hurling pebbles that turn into small cakes.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice eats one and shrinks herself, allowing her to flee into the forest.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She meets a Caterpillar seated on a mushroom and smoking a hookah.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Under the Caterpillar's questioning, Alice begins to admit to her current identity crisis, compounded by her inability to remember a poem.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Before crawling away, the Caterpillar says that a bite of one side of the mushroom will make her larger, while a bite from the other side will make her smaller.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] During a period of trial and error, Alice's neck extends between the treetops, frightening a pigeon who mistakes her for a serpent.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] After shrinking to an appropriate height, Alice arrives at the home of a Duchess, who owns a perpetually grinning Cheshire Cat.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Duchess's baby, whom she hands to Alice, transforms into a piglet, which Alice releases into the woods.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Cheshire Cat appears to Alice and directs her toward the Hatter and March Hare before disappearing, leaving his grin behind.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice finds the Hatter, March Hare, and a sleepy Dormouse in the middle of a tea party.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Hatter explains that it is always 6 p.m.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] (tea time) – the consequence of his having quarrelled with Time.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Noticing a door in a tree, Alice passes through and finds herself back in the room from the beginning of her journey.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She takes the key and opens the door to the garden, which turns out to be the croquet court of the Queen of Hearts, whose guard consists of living playing cards.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice participates in a croquet game, in which hedgehogs are used as balls, flamingos are used as mallets, and soldiers act as hoops.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Queen is short-tempered, constantly ordering beheadings.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] When the Cheshire Cat's lone head appears, the Queen orders its beheading, an act which appears impossible in the absence of a body from which to sever it.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice prompts the Queen to release the Duchess, now in prison.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice meets a Gryphon and a Mock Turtle, who dance to the Lobster Quadrille while Alice recites (rather incorrectly) a poem.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Mock Turtle sings "Beautiful Soup", during which the Gryphon drags Alice away for a trial, in which the Knave of Hearts stands accused of stealing the Queen's tarts.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The trial is conducted by the King of Hearts, and the jury is composed of animals that Alice previously met.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice gradually grows in size and confidence, allowing herself increasingly frequent remarks on the irrationality of the proceedings.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Queen eventually commands Alice's beheading, but Alice scoffs that her guard is only a pack of playing cards.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The cards rise up into the air and come swarming down upon her.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice wakes from her dream to find her sister brushing leaves from her face.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice tells her about her adventures, then runs in for her tea, leaving her sister on the bank to imagine all the curious happenings for herself.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In *The Annotated Alice*, Martin Gardner provides background information for the characters.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The members of the boating party that first heard Carroll's tale show up in chapter 3 ("A Caucus-Race and a Long Tale").
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice Liddell is there, while Carroll is caricatured as the Dodo (Lewis Carroll was a pen name for Charles Lutwidge Dodgson; because he stuttered when he spoke, he sometimes pronounced his last name as "Dodo-Dodgson").
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Duck refers to Robinson Duckworth, and the Lory and Eaglet to Alice Liddell's sisters Lorina and Edith.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Bill the Lizard may be a play on the name of British Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] One of Tenniel's illustrations in *Through the Looking-Glass*—the 1871 sequel to *Alice*—depicts the character referred to as the "Man in White Paper" (whom Alice meets on a train) as a caricature of Disraeli, wearing a paper hat.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The illustrations of the Lion and the Unicorn (also in *Looking-Glass*) look like Tenniel's *Punch* illustrations of William Ewart Gladstone and Disraeli, although Gardner says there is "no proof" that they were intended to represent these politicians.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Gardner has suggested that the Hatter is a reference to Theophilus Carter, an Oxford furniture dealer, and that Tenniel apparently drew the Hatter to resemble Carter, on a suggestion of Carroll's.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Dormouse tells a story about three little sisters named Elsie, Lacie, and Tillie.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] These are the Liddell sisters: Elsie is L.C.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] (Lorina Charlotte); Tillie is Edith (her family nickname is Matilda); and Lacie is an anagram of Alice.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Mock Turtle speaks of a drawling-master, "an old conger eel", who came once a week to teach "Drawling, Stretching, and Fainting in Coils".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] This is a reference to the art critic John Ruskin, who came once a week to the Liddell house to teach the children to draw, sketch, and paint in oils.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The Mock Turtle sings "Turtle Soup", a parody of a song called "Star of the Evening, Beautiful Star", which the Liddells sang for Carroll.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Cohen reads *Alice* as a *roman à clef* populated with real figures from Carroll's life.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice is based on Alice Liddell; the Dodo is Carroll; Wonderland is Oxford; even the Mad Hatter's Tea Party, according to Cohen, is a send-up of Alice's own birthday party.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The critic Jan Susina rejects Cohen's account, arguing that Alice the character bears a tenuous relationship with Alice Liddell.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Beyond its refashioning of Carroll's everyday life, Cohen argues, *Alice* critiques Victorian ideals of childhood.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It is an account of "the child's plight in Victorian upper-class society", in which Alice's mistreatment by the creatures of Wonderland reflects Carroll's own mistreatment by older people as a child.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In the eighth chapter, three cards are painting the roses on a rose tree red, because they had accidentally planted a white-rose tree that the Queen of Hearts hates.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] According to Wilfrid Scott-Giles, the rose motif in *Alice* alludes to the English Wars of the Roses: red roses symbolised the House of Lancaster, and white roses the rival House of York.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Pat's "digging for apples" is a cross-language pun, as *pomme de terre* (literally; "apple of the earth") means potato and *pomme* means apple.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The sixth case, *mure* (ablative) is absent from Alice's recitation.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Nilson suggests that Alice's missing ablative is a pun on her father Henry Liddell's work on the standard *A Greek-English Lexicon*, since ancient Greek does not have an ablative case.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Further, mousa (μούσα, meaning muse) was a standard model noun in Greek textbooks of the time in paradigms of the first declension, short-alpha noun.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Mathematics and logic are central to *Alice*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] As Carroll was a mathematician at Christ Church, it has been suggested that there are many references and mathematical concepts in both this story and *Through the Looking-Glass*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Literary scholar Melanie Bayley asserts in the *New Scientist* magazine that Carroll wrote *Alice in Wonderland* in its final form as a satire on mid-19th century mathematics.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carina Garland notes how the world is "expressed via representations of food and appetite", naming Alice's frequent desire for consumption (of both food and words), her 'Curious Appetites'.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Often, the idea of eating coincides to make gruesome images.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Wonderland is a rule-bound world, but its rules are not those of our world.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The literary scholar Daniel Bivona writes that *Alice* is characterised by "gamelike social structures".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She trusts in instructions from the beginning, drinking from the bottle labelled "drink me" after recalling, during her descent, that children who do not follow the rules often meet terrible fates.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Unlike the creatures of Wonderland, who approach their world's wonders uncritically, Alice continues to look for rules as the story progresses.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Gillian Beer suggests that Alice looks for rules to soothe her anxiety, while Carroll may have hunted for rules because he struggled with the implications of the non-Euclidean geometry then in development.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The manuscript was illustrated by Carroll, who added 37 illustrations—printed in a facsimile edition in 1887.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] John Tenniel provided 42 wood-engraved illustrations for the 1865 published version of the book.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The first print run was destroyed (or sold in the US) at Carroll's request because Tenniel was dissatisfied with the printing quality.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] There are only 22 known first edition copies in existence.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The book was reprinted and published in 1866.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel's detailed black-and-white drawings remain the definitive depiction of the characters.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] — The V&A museum on Tenniel's illustrations for the novel.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel's illustrations of Alice do not portray the real Alice Liddell, who had dark hair and a short fringe.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 1911, Harry Theaker, with Tenniel's approval, was commissioned by Macmillan to colour sixteen of Tenniel's plates for an *Alice* edition and her dress was blue – and has remained so in the popular mind ever since.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Alice* has provided a challenge for other illustrators, including those of 1907 by Charles Pears and the full series of colour plates and line-drawings by Harry Rountree published in the (inter-War) Children's Press (Glasgow) edition.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] To mark the 200th anniversary of Tenniel's birth, in 2020 Chris Riddell provided illustrations for a new edition of the novel.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll first met Alexander Macmillan, a high-powered London publisher, on 19 October 1863.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] His firm, Macmillan Publishers, agreed to publish *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* by sometime in 1864.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll financed the initial print run, possibly because it gave him more editorial authority than other financing methods.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He managed publication details such as typesetting and engaged illustrators and translators.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Macmillan had published *The Water-Babies*, also a children's fantasy, in 1863, and suggested its design as a basis for *Alice*'s.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll saw a specimen copy in May 1865.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] 2,000 copies were printed by July, but Tenniel objected to their quality, and Carroll instructed Macmillan to halt publication so they could be reprinted.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In August, he engaged Richard Clay as an alternative printer for a new run of 2,000.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The reprint cost £600, paid entirely by Carroll.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He received the first copy of Clay's edition on 9 November 1865.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Macmillan finally published the new edition, printed by Richard Clay, in November 1865.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll requested a red binding, deeming it appealing to young readers.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A new edition, released in December 1865 for the Christmas market but carrying an 1866 date, was quickly printed.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The text blocks of the original edition were removed from the binding and sold with Carroll's permission to the New York publishing house of D.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The binding for the Appleton *Alice* was identical to the 1866 Macmillan *Alice*, except for the publisher's name at the foot of the spine.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The title page of the Appleton *Alice* was an insert cancelling the original Macmillan title page of 1865 and bearing the New York publisher's imprint and the date 1866.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Alice* was a publishing sensation, beloved by children and adults alike.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Oscar Wilde was a fan; Queen Victoria was also an avid reader of the book.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She reportedly enjoyed *Alice* enough that she asked for Carroll's next book, which turned out to be a mathematical treatise; Carroll denied this.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* has been translated into 174 languages.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] — Walt Disney in *The American Weekly*, 1946.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Harvey Darton argued in a 1932 book that *Alice* ended an era of didacticism in children's literature, inaugurating a new era in which writing for children aimed to "delight or entertain".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 2014, Robert McCrum named *Alice* "one of the best loved in the English canon" and called it "perhaps the greatest, possibly most influential, and certainly the most world-famous Victorian English fiction".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A 2020 review in *Time* states: "The book changed young people's literature.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It helped to replace stiff Victorian didacticism with a looser, sillier, nonsense style that reverberated through the works of language-loving 20th-century authors as different as James Joyce, Douglas Adams and Dr.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Seuss." Joe Sommerlad in *The Independent* writes that Roald Dahl "owes a debt to the "Drink Me" episode in *Alice*" in regard to Dahl's *George's Marvellous Medicine* where the protagonist's grandmother drinks a potion and is blown up to the size of a farmhouse.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The protagonist of the story, Alice, has been recognised as a cultural icon.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 2006, *Alice in Wonderland* was named among the icons of England in a public vote.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Books for children in the *Alice* mould emerged as early as 1869 and continued to appear throughout the late 19th century.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Released in 1903, the British silent film *Alice in Wonderland* was the first screen adaptation of the book.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Labelled "a dauntless, no-nonsense heroine" by the *Guardian*, the character of the plucky, yet proper, Alice has proven immensely popular and inspired similar heroines in literature and pop culture, many also named Alice in homage.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The book has inspired numerous film and television adaptations, which have multiplied, as the original work is now in the public domain in all jurisdictions.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Musical works inspired by *Alice* include the Beatles's song "Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds"; songwriter John Lennon attributed the song's fantastical imagery to his reading of Carroll's books.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Argentine prog-rock band Seru Giran used *Alice* as a metaphor to represent the political climate in Argentina during the 1970s in their song "Canción de Alicia en el país".
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A popular figure in Japan since the country opened up to the West in the late 19th century, Alice has been a popular subject for writers of manga and a source of inspiration for Japanese fashion, in particular Lolita fashion.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The first full major production was *Alice in Wonderland*, a musical play in London's West End by Henry Savile Clarke and Walter Slaughter, which premiered at the Prince of Wales Theatre in 1886.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Twelve-year-old actress Phoebe Carlo (the first to play Alice) was personally selected by Carroll for the role.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll attended a performance on 30 December 1886, writing in his diary that he enjoyed it.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The musical was frequently revived during West End Christmas seasons during the four decades after its premiere, including a London production at the Globe Theatre in 1888, with Isa Bowman as Alice.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] As the book and its sequel are Carroll's most widely recognised works, they have also inspired numerous live performances, including plays, operas, ballets, and traditional English pantomimes.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] These works range from fairly faithful adaptations to those that use the story as a basis for new works.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Eva Le Gallienne's stage adaptation of the *Alice* books premiered on 12 December 1932 and ended its run in May 1933.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The production was revived in New York in 1947 and 1982.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A community theatre production of *Alice* was Olivia de Havilland's first foray onto the stage.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Prentice premiered at the Shakespeare Memorial Theatre, Stratford-upon-Avon in 1947, and was in turn adapted for television by John Glyn-Jones and shown by the BBC on Christmas Day 1948.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The BBC screened another adaptation of Prentice's play in 1956.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Joseph Papp staged *Alice in Concert* at the Public Theater in New York City in 1980.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Elizabeth Swados wrote the book, lyrics, and music based on both *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* and *Through the Looking-Glass*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Papp and Swados had previously produced a version of it at the New York Shakespeare Festival.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Meryl Streep played Alice, the White Queen, and Humpty Dumpty.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The cast also included Debbie Allen, Michael Jeter, and Mark Linn-Baker.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Performed on a bare stage with the actors in modern dress, the play is a loose adaptation, with song styles ranging the globe.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The 2001 Adrian Mitchell play, *Alice in Wonderland and Through the Looking-Glass*, commissioned by the Royal Shakespeare Company, is notable for adapting almost every scene from both books.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The 1992 musical theatre production *Alice* used both books as its inspiration.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It also employs scenes with Carroll, a young Alice Liddell, and an adult Alice Liddell, to frame the story.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Paul Schmidt wrote the play, with Tom Waits and Kathleen Brennan writing the music.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Although the original production in Hamburg, Germany, received only a small audience, Tom Waits released the songs as the album *Alice* in 2002.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Joseph Horovitz composed an *Alice in Wonderland* ballet commissioned by the London Festival Ballet in 1953.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] It was performed frequently in England and the US.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] A ballet by Christopher Wheeldon and Nicholas Wright commissioned for the Royal Ballet entitled *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* premiered in February 2011 at the Royal Opera House in London.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The ballet was based on the novel Wheeldon grew up reading as a child and is generally faithful to the original story, although some critics claimed it may have been too faithful.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Unsuk Chin's opera *Alice in Wonderland* premiered in 2007 at the Bavarian State Opera and was hailed as World Premiere of the Year by the German opera magazine *Opernwelt*.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Gerald Barry's 2016 one-act opera, *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*, first staged in 2020 at the Royal Opera House, is a conflation of the two *Alice* books.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 2022, the Opéra national du Rhin performed the ballet *Alice*, with a score by Philip Glass, in Mulhouse, France.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Following the establishment of a memorial fund in 1932 to celebrate the centenary of Carroll's birth, characters from the book were depicted in the stained glass windows of his hometown church, All Saints', in Daresbury, Cheshire, which was dedicated in 1935.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Another commemoration of Carroll's work in his home county of Cheshire is the granite sculpture *The Mad Hatter's Tea Party*, located in Warrington.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] International works based on the book include the Alice in Wonderland statue in Central Park, New York, and the Alice statue in Rymill Park, Adelaide, Australia.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 2015, *Alice* characters were featured on a series of UK postage stamps issued by the Royal Mail to mark the 150th anniversary of the publication of the book.
[src:oxford-university-press/alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 2021, the Royal Mint issued their first *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* commemorative coin collection, including a £5 coin featuring Alice and the Cheshire Cat (inspired by Tenniel's original illustration).
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The college entrance is on the north side of High Street, whilst it has a long frontage onto Radcliffe Square.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] To its east is The Queen's College, whilst Hertford College is to the north of All Souls.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The current warden (head of the college) is Sir John Vickers, a graduate of Oriel College, Oxford.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The college was founded by Henry VI of England and Henry Chichele (fellow of New College and Archbishop of Canterbury), in 1438, to commemorate the victims of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The Statutes provided for a warden and 40 fellows; all to take Holy Orders: 24 to study arts and theology; and 16 to study civil or canon law.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Today the college is primarily a research institution, with no student members.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] All Souls did formerly have students: Robert Hovenden (Warden of the college from 1571 to 1614) introduced undergraduates to provide the fellows with *servientes* (household servants), but this was abandoned by the end of the Commonwealth.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Four Bible Clerks remained on the foundation until 1924.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] For over five hundred years All Souls College admitted only men; women were first allowed to join the college as fellows in 1979, the same year as many other previously all-male colleges in the university.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The American philosopher Susan Hurley became the first female fellow in 1981.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Conservative fellows opposed this change.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Once, upon encountering a woman fellow, the geneticist E.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Ford swung his umbrella at her and shouted "Out of my way, henbird!".
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The All Souls College Library (formerly known as the Codrington Library) was founded through a 1710 bequest from Christopher Codrington (1668–1710), a fellow of the college and a wealthy slave and sugar plantation owner.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Codrington was an undergraduate at Oxford and later became colonial governor of the Leeward Islands.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Christopher Codrington was born in Barbados, and amassed a fortune from his sugar plantation in the West Indies.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Under the terms of his will Codrington bequeathed books worth £6,000 to the college in addition to £10,000 in currency for the library to be rebuilt and endowed.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The new library was completed in 1751 to the designs of Nicholas Hawksmoor and has been in continuous use since then.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Today the library comprises some 185,000 items, about a third of which were published before 1800.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The collections are particularly strong in law and history (especially military history).
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Sir Christopher Wren was a fellow from 1653.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The design of the sundial, produced in 1658 for the south wall of the Chapel, is attributed to Wren.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The sundial was moved to the quadrangle (above the central entrance to the Library) in 1877.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] In 2020, the College decided to cease referring to the Library as 'The Codrington Library' as part of a set of "steps to address the problematic nature of the Codrington legacy", which comes from wealth derived from slave plantations.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Built between 1438 and 1442, the college chapel remained largely unchanged until the Commonwealth.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Oxford, having been a largely Royalist stronghold, suffered under the Puritans' wrath.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The 42 misericords date from the Chapel's building, and show a resemblance to the misericords at St Mary's Church, Higham Ferrers.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Both may have been carved by Richard Tyllock.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] During the 1660s a screen was installed in the Chapel, which was based on a design by Wren.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] However, this screen needed to be rebuilt by 1713.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] By the mid-19th century the Chapel was in great need of renovation, and so the current structure is heavily influenced by Victorian design ideals.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] There have been a number of rearrangements and repairs of the stained glass windows, but much of the original medieval glass survives.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] All services at the chapel are according to the *Book of Common Prayer*; the *King James Bible* is also used rather than more modern translations.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] All Souls is one of the wealthiest colleges in Oxford with a financial endowment of £486.7 million (2023).
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Approximately 95% of its annual income is derived from its endowment as the College does not receive any income from tuition fees.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] While tutors may advise their students to sit for the All Souls examination fellowship, the examination is open to anybody who fulfils the eligibility criteria and the college does not issue invitations to candidates to sit.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Every year in early March, the college hosts an open evening for women, offering women interested in the examination fellowship an opportunity to find out more about the exam process and to meet members of the college.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Each year several dozen candidates typically sit the examination.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Two examination fellows are usually elected each year, although the college has awarded a single place or three places in some years, and on rare occasions made no award.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The competition, offered since 1878 and open to women since 1979, is held over two days in late September, with two papers of three hours each per day.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] It has been described as "the hardest exam in the world".
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Two papers (the 'specialist papers') are on a single subject of the candidate's choice; the options are classics, English literature, economics, history, law, philosophy, and politics.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Two papers (the 'general papers') are on general subjects.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] For each general examination, candidates choose three questions from a list.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Before 2010 candidates also faced another examination, a free-form "Essay" on a single, pre-selected word.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Four to six finalists are invited to a viva voce or oral examination.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Previously, these candidates were then invited to dinner with about 75 members of the college.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The dinner did not form part of the assessment, but was intended as a reward for those candidates who had reached the latter stages of the selection process.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] However, the dinner has been discontinued as the college felt candidates worried too often that it was part of the assessment process.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] About a dozen examination fellows are at the college at any one time.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] There are no compulsory teaching or requirements, although examination fellows must pursue a course of study or research at some point within their first two years of fellowship.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] They can study anything for nothing at Oxford with room and board.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] As "Londoners" they can pursue approved non-academic careers if desired, with a reduced stipend, as long as they pursue academia on a part-time basis and attend weekend dinners at the college during their first academic year.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] As of 2011 each examination fellow receives a stipend of £14,842 annually for the first two years; the stipend then varies depending on whether the fellow pursues an academic career.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Until 1979, women were not permitted to put themselves forward for fellowships at All Souls.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] There are also a number of professorial fellows who hold their fellowships by virtue of their University post.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Fellows of the college include the Chichele professors, who hold statutory professorships at the University of Oxford named in honour of Henry Chichele, a founder of the college.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Fellowship of the college has accompanied the award of a Chichele chair since 1870.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Probably the best known former Chichele Professor is Sir Isaiah Berlin.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Perhaps the best known former Professor of the History of War was Cyril Falls.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The Chichele Lectures are a prestigious series of lectures formally established in 1912 and sponsored by All Souls College.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The lectures were initially restricted to foreign history, but have since been expanded to include law, political theory, economic theory, as well as foreign and British history.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] Traditionally the lectures were delivered by a single speaker, but it is now common for several speakers to deliver lectures on a common theme.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] During the hunt the Lord Mallard is preceded by a man bearing a pole to which a mallard is tied – originally a live bird, latterly either dead (1901) or carved from wood (2001).
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The last mallard ceremony was in 2001 and the next is due in 2101.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] The precise origin of the custom is not known, but it dates from at least 1632.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] A benign parody of this custom has been portrayed as the Unseen University's "Megapode chase" in Sir Terry Pratchett's 2009 novel *Unseen Academicals*.
[src:oxford-university-press/all-souls-college-oxford] In the 2011 historical fantasy novel *A Discovery of Witches* by Deborah Harkness, main character and vampire Matthew Clairmont is a Fellow of All Souls College, having passed the examination in 1989 after writing an essay on the topic of "desire".
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It is a department of the University of Oxford.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It is governed by a group of 15 academics, the Delegates of the Press, appointed by the vice-chancellor of the University of Oxford.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Delegates of the Press are led by the Secretary to the Delegates, who serves as OUP's chief executive and as its major representative on other university bodies.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Oxford University Press has had a similar governance structure since the 17th century.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The press is located on Walton Street, Oxford, opposite Somerville College, in the inner suburb of Jericho.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] For the last 400 years, OUP has focused primarily on the publication of pedagogical texts.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It continues this tradition today by publishing academic journals, dictionaries, English language resources, bibliographies, books on Indology, music, classics, literature, and history, as well as Bibles and atlases.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP has offices around the world, primarily in locations that were once part of the British Empire.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The University of Oxford began printing around 1480 and became a major printer of Bibles, prayer books, and scholarly works.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Oxford's chancellor Archbishop William Laud consolidated the legal status of the university's printing in the 1630s and petitioned Charles I for rights that would enable Oxford to compete with the Stationers' Company and the King's Printer.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] He obtained a succession of royal grants, and Oxford's "Great Charter" in 1636 gave the university the right to print "all manner of books".
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Laud also obtained the "privilege" from the Crown of printing the King James or Authorized Version of Scripture at Oxford.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] This privilege created substantial returns over the next 250 years.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Following the English Civil War, Vice-chancellor John Fell, Dean of Christ Church, Bishop of Oxford, and Secretary to the Delegates was determined to install printing presses in 1668, making it the university's first central print shop.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1674, OUP began to print a broadsheet calendar, known as the *Oxford Almanack,* that was produced annually without interruption from 1674 to 2019.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The early 18th century marked a lull in the press's expansion.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It suffered from the absence of any figure comparable to Fell.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The business was rescued by the intervention of a single Delegate, William Blackstone.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The university moved to adopt all of Blackstone's reforms by 1760.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] By the late 18th century, the press had become more focused.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1825, the Delegates bought land on Walton Street.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Buildings were constructed from plans drawn up by Daniel Robertson and Edward Blore, and the press moved into them in 1830.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The press then entered an era of enormous change.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1830, it was still a joint-stock printing business in an academic backwater, offering learned works to a relatively small readership of scholars and clerics At this time, Thomas Combe joined the press and became the university's Printer until he died in 1872.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Combe was a better businessman than most Delegates but still no innovator: he failed to grasp the huge commercial potential of India paper, which grew into one of Oxford's most profitable trade secrets in later years.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Even so, Combe earned a fortune through his shares in the business and the acquisition and renovation of the bankrupt paper mill at Wolvercote.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Combe showed little interest, however, in producing fine printed work at the press.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The best-known text associated with his print shop was the flawed first edition of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*, printed by Oxford at the expense of its author Lewis Carroll (Charles Lutwidge Dodgson) in 1865.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It took the 1850 Royal Commission on the workings of the university and a new Secretary, Bartholomew Price, to shake up the press.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Under Price, the press began to take on its modern shape.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] For example, in 1875, the Delegates approved the series *Sacred Books of the East* under the editorship of Friedrich Max Müller, bringing a vast range of religious thought to a wider readership.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Equally, Price moved OUP towards publishing in its own right.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The press had ended its relationship with Parker's in 1863 and, in 1870, bought a small London bindery for some Bible work.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Macmillan's contract ended in 1880 and was not renewed.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] By this time, Oxford also had a London warehouse for Bible stock in Paternoster Row, and in 1880, its manager, Henry Frowde (1841–1927), was given the formal title of Publisher to the university.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Frowde came from the book trade, not the university, and remained an enigma to many.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1884, the year he retired as Secretary, the Delegates bought back the last shares in the business.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The press was now owned wholly by the university, with its own paper mill, print shop, bindery, and warehouse.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Its output had increased to include school books and modern scholarly texts such as James Clerk Maxwell's *A Treatise on Electricity & Magnetism* (1873), which proved fundamental to Einstein's thought.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Without abandoning its traditions or quality of work, Price began to turn OUP into an alert, modern publisher.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1879, he also took on the publication that led that process to its conclusion: the massive project that became the *Oxford English Dictionary* (OED).
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Offered to Oxford by James Murray and the Philological Society, the "New English Dictionary" was a grand academic and patriotic undertaking.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Lengthy negotiations led to a formal contract.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Murray was to edit a work estimated to take ten years and to cost approximately £9,000.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Dictionary began appearing in print in 1884, but the first edition was not completed until 1928, 13 years after Murray's death, costing around £375,000.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The next Secretary, Philip Lyttelton Gell, was appointed by the Vice-Chancellor Benjamin Jowett in 1884 but struggled and was finally dismissed in 1897.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Assistant Secretary, Charles Cannan, was instrumental in Gell's removal.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] By the early 20th century, OUP expanded its overseas trade, partly due to the efforts of Humphrey Milford, the publisher of the University of Oxford from 1913 to 1945.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The 1920s saw skyrocketing prices of both materials and labour.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Paper was hard to come by and had to be imported from South America through trading companies.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Economies and markets slowly recovered as the 1920s progressed.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1928, the press's imprint read 'London, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Leipzig, Toronto, Melbourne, Cape Town, Bombay, Calcutta, Madras and Shanghai'.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Not all of these were full-fledged branches: in Leipzig, there was a depot run by H.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In India, the Branch depots in Bombay, Madras, and Calcutta were imposing establishments with sizeable stock inventories, for the Presidencies themselves were large markets, and the educational representatives there dealt mostly with upcountry trade.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1923, OUP established a Music Department.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] At the time, such musical publishing enterprises, however, were rare.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP bought an Anglo-French Music Company and all its facilities, connections, and resources.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] This concentration provided OUP two mutually reinforcing benefits: a niche in music publishing unoccupied by potential competitors and a branch of music performance and composition that the English themselves had largely neglected.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Depression of 1929 dried profits from the Americas to a trickle, and India became 'the one bright spot' in an otherwise dismal picture.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Bombay was the nodal point for distribution to Africa and onward sale to Australasia, and people who trained at the three major depots later moved to pioneer branches in Africa and Southeast Asia.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1927–1934 Oxford University Press, Inc., New York, was reorganized by Geoffrey Cumberlege to return it to profitability from the lows of the Depression years.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] (In 1945–1956, Cumberlege would succeed Milford as publisher to the University of Oxford).
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] By the end of 2021, OUP USA had published eighteen Pulitzer Prize–winning books.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In March 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, its Bookshop on the High Street closed.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] On 27 August 2021, OUP closed Oxuniprint, its printing division.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The closure marked the final chapter of OUP's centuries-long history of printing.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP came to be known as "(**The**) **Clarendon Press**" when printing moved from the Sheldonian Theatre to the Clarendon Building in Broad Street in 1713.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The name continued to be used when OUP moved to its present site in Oxford in 1830.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The label "Clarendon Press" took on a new meaning when OUP began publishing books through its London office in the early 20th century.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] To distinguish the two offices, London books were labelled "Oxford University Press" publications, while those from Oxford were labelled "Clarendon Press" books.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] This labelling ceased in the 1970s when the London office of OUP closed.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Today, OUP reserves "Clarendon Press" as an imprint for Oxford publications of particular academic importance.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP as **Oxford Journals** has also been a major publisher of academic journals, both in the sciences and the humanities; as of 2024 it publishes more than 500 journals on behalf of learned societies around the world.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The "Oxford Open" model applies to the majority of their journals.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP is a member of the Open Access Scholarly Publishers Association.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP is a signatory of the SDG Publishers Compact, and has taken steps to support the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) in the publishing industry.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] These include the publishing of a new series of Oxford Open Journals, including *Oxford Open Climate Change*, *Oxford Open Energy*, *Oxford Open Immunology*, *Oxford Open Infrastructure and Health*, and *Oxford Open Digital Health*.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Oxford University Press publishes a variety of dictionaries (e.g.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] *Let's Go*), English language exams (e.g.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Oxford Test of English and the Oxford Placement Test), bibliographies (e.g., *Oxford Bibliographies Online*), miscellaneous series such as *Very Short Introductions*, and books on Indology, music, classics, literature, history, Bibles, and atlases.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Many of these are published under the Oxford Languages brand.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Since 2001, Oxford University Press has financially supported the Clarendon bursary, a University of Oxford graduate scholarship scheme.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In February 1989, Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini issued a fatwa urging the execution of British author Salman Rushdie and of all involved in the publication of his novel *The Satanic Verses*.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Rushdie went into hiding, and an international movement began to boycott book trading with Iran.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] There was, therefore, outrage when, in April 1989, OUP broke the worldwide embargo and chose to attend the Tehran Book Fair.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP justified this by saying, "We deliberated about it quite deeply but felt it certainly wasn't in our interests, or Iran's as a whole, to stay away." *The New York Times* and *The Sunday Times* both condemned Oxford's decision.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1990, in the UK Court of Appeal, author Andrew Malcolm won a landmark legal judgment against Oxford University (Press) for its breach of a contract to publish his philosophical text *Making Names*.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Reporting on the verdict in *The Observer*, Laurence Marks wrote, "It is the first time in living memory that Grub Street has won such a victory over its oppressors".
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Appeal Court judges were highly critical of Oxford's conduct of the affair and the litigation.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The case ended in July 1992 with a Tomlin order, a damages settlement under which the servants and agents of Oxford University are permanently barred from denigrating Malcolm or *Making Names*, rendering it the first book in literary history to be afforded such legal protection.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The case was reported to have cost Oxford over £500,000.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In November 1998, OUP announced the closure, on commercial grounds, of its modern poetry list.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Andrew Potter, OUP's director of music, trade paperbacks and Bibles, told *The Times* that the list "just about breaks even.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The university expects us to operate on commercial grounds, especially in this day and age." In the same article, the poet D.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Enright, who had been with OUP since 1979, said, "There was no warning.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Even the poetry editor didn't know....The money involved is peanuts.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It's a good list, built up over many years." In February 1999, Arts Minister Alan Howarth made a speech in Oxford in which he denounced the closure: "OUP is not merely a business.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It is a department of the University of Oxford and has charitable status.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It is part of a great university, which the Government supports financially and which exists to develop and transmit our intellectual culture....It is a perennial complaint by the English faculty that the barbarians are at the gate.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Since the 1940s, both OUP and the Cambridge University Press (CUP), had made applications to the Inland Revenue for exemption from corporate tax.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In November 1975, CUP's chief executive Geoffrey Cass again applied to the Inland Revenue, and a year later, CUP's tax exemption was quietly conceded.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP's Chief Executive George Richardson followed suit in 1977.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] OUP's tax exemption was granted in 1978.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The issue was only brought to public attention due to press interest in OUP following the poetry list closure controversy.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 1999, the campaigner Andrew Malcolm published his second book, *The Remedy*, where he alleged that OUP breached its 1978 tax-exemption conditions.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] This was reported in a front-page article in *The Oxford Times*, along with OUP's response.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In March 2001, after a 28-year battle with the Indian tax authorities, OUP lost its tax exemption in India.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The Supreme Court ruled that OUP was not tax exempt in the subcontinent "because it does not carry out any university activities there but acts simply as a commercial publisher".
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] To pay off back taxes, owed since the 1970s, OUP was obliged to sell its Mumbai headquarters building, Oxford House.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] *The Bookseller* reported that "The case has again raised questions about OUP's status in the UK".
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 2003, Joel Rickett of *The Bookseller* wrote an article in *The Guardian* describing the resentment of commercial rivals at OUP's tax exemption.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Rickett accurately predicted that the funds which would have been paid in tax were "likely to be used to confirm OUP's dominance by buying up other publishers." Between 1989 and 2018, OUP bought out over 70 rival book and journal publishers.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 2007, with the new "public benefit" requirement of the revised Charities Act, the issue was re-examined with particular reference to OUP.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In the same year, Malcolm obtained and posted the documents of OUP's applications to the Inland Revenue for tax exemption in the 1940s and 1950s (unsuccessful) and the 1970s (successful).
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 2008, CUP's and OUP's privilege was attacked by rival publishers.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In 2009, *The Guardian* invited Andrew Malcolm to write an article on the subject.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In July 2012, the UK's Serious Fraud Office found OUP's branches in Kenya and Tanzania guilty of bribery to obtain school bookselling contracts sponsored by the World Bank.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Oxford was fined £1.9 million "in recognition of sums it received which were generated through unlawful conduct" and barred from applying for World Bank-financed projects for three years.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In December 2023, concerns were raised that OUP had published an academic paper based on genetic data taken from the Uyghur population of Xinjiang, a Turkic ethnic group in China.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Rhys Blakely, a science correspondent for *The Times*, reported: "The research has been published online by Oxford University Press (OUP) in a journal that receives financial support from China's Ministry of Justice.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] The highly unusual deal will raise fears that Oxford risks becoming entangled in human rights abuses against the Uighur community.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] It will also add to concerns over China's efforts to influence UK academia." In February, OUP announced that it was carrying out internal investigations into two further studies, based on DNA taken from China's Xibe ethnic minority.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] On 17 May, *The Times* reported that Oxford had retracted the two studies, quoting a statement from the OUP: "Earlier this year, we were alerted to concerns regarding two papers in Forensics Sciences Research.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] In July 2025, OUP ended its publication of *Forensic Sciences Research* (FSR), a journal sponsored by China's Ministry of Justice, following ethical concerns related to research involving DNA data from Uyghur and other ethnic minorities in China.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Critics raised issues about the lack of meaningful consent from participants, particularly in regions like Xinjiang, where state surveillance and coercion are prevalent.
[src:oxford-university-press/oxford-university-press] Several studies published in the journal were conducted or funded by Chinese police and security agencies, raising questions about the independence and ethical standards of the research.
